Readme file for PharmaGist program

##########################################################################
# Installation
##########################################################################

No installation is required, you can add the PharmaGist
directory to your path for convinient usage.

In order to visualize the results jmol applet and web browser are required.
Jmol can be downloaded from here:
http://sourceforge.net/projects/jmol/files/

##########################################################################
# Program Input Preparation
##########################################################################

1. Prepare your molecules in mol2 files. You have several input options:
   1. all the molecules in single mol2 file
   2. several mol2 files with one or more molecules. in this case prepare
      a file with all filenames separated by newline:
         1.mol2
         2.mol2
         ....

   Please note that for database search, all the molecules should be
   in single mol2 file.

2. prepare config file:
   1. copy default config file ("pharmagist.config") to you run directory. 
   2. update paths to dock_flex_drive2.tbl and dock_flex.defn files in 
      the installation directory in the config file.
   3. update path to your jmol applet files in the config file.

##########################################################################
# Running the program
##########################################################################

type:

pharmagist.linux -c pharmagist.config

this will print program usage

Note: use pharmagist64.linux for 64BIT machines

1. pharmacophore detection
--------------------------
   if your input files are in single mol2 file, type:

--> pharmagist.linux -c pharmagist.config single.mol2       

    otherwise, specify the name of the file with mol2 filenames:

--> pharmagist.linux -c pharmagist.config -f input_files.txt

2. database search
------------------
   as in pharmacophore detection, just add -d database.mol2

--> pharmagist.linux -c pharmagist.config single.mol2 -d database.mol2

   in this case pharmacophore search will be followed by database
   search.  if you want to use previous pharmacophore search, use -p
   option to give the program phrmacophore .pha file that was
   generated by pharmacophore search:

--> ./pharmagist.linux -c pharmagist.config -p output/1.pha -d database.mol2

3. additional program options
-----------------------------

-i option tells the program to try each input molecule as a pivot in
 the pharmacophore detection step. Without '-i' the first input molecule
 serves as a pivot.

-o option lets you specify output directory, default is output

-t option can be used to test validity of your input mol2 files

Other program parameters can be changed in the config file.
The explanations are in this file. See references below for more detailed
information.

##########################################################################
# Program Output
##########################################################################

Pharmagist output should be viewed through web browser. The output
interface is the same as on the webserver. Please see website for explanation
http://bioinfo3d.cs.tau.ac.il/pharma/help.html

The output directory contains index.html file that should be open in
the web browser.

If you don't see jmol applets there maybe two possible reasons: 

1. If you do not see applet window and checkboxes in the tables
than your browser can not find jmol files. Please check your path in
config file again.  

2. If you see a window and checkboxes, however the molecules do not
load, your browser may not support it, try a different web browser.
if you can see jmol applet on our website
http://bioinfo3d.cs.tau.ac.il/pharma/help.html 
than it is the first problem with jmol path.

You can also find mol2 files with ligand alignments and pharmacophore
features in the output folder. You can display them in your favorite
viewer.

##########################################################################
# References
##########################################################################

If you use PharmaGist, please cite:

1. Deterministic pharmacophore detection via multiple flexible 
alignment of drug-like molecules.
Schneidman-Duhovny D, Dror O, Inbar Y, Nussinov R, Wolfson HJ.
J Comput Biol. 2008 Sep;15(7):737-54.
 
2. PharmaGist: a webserver for ligand-based pharmacophore detection.
Schneidman-Duhovny D, Dror O, Inbar Y, Nussinov R, Wolfson HJ 
Nucleic Acids Res. 2008 Jul 1;36(Web Server issue):W223-8.
